00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:05.016
What's wrong?

00:36:05.016 --> 00:36:06.050
And everything is fine.

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:09.260
I just don't think
he'll dig into it.

00:36:09.260 --> 00:36:11.540
Maybe Mark is really
that kind of person

00:36:11.540 --> 00:36:13.430
that's open to talking
about it, but how

00:36:13.430 --> 00:36:17.870
do you talk to a 28-year-old
guy about these deep questions?

00:36:17.870 --> 00:36:19.760
MANDY LEN CATRON:
That's a great question.

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:23.450
I mean, I think it's
worth noting that the 36

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:27.590
questions start
out really casually

00:36:27.590 --> 00:36:30.390
and they get more
intimate as you go along.

00:36:30.390 --> 00:36:33.290
So the first one is, if you
could have dinner with anyone

00:36:33.290 --> 00:36:34.970
living or dead, who
would it be, which

00:36:34.970 --> 00:36:38.210
I think is just interesting.

00:36:38.210 --> 00:36:40.340
And I think maybe if
you just position it

00:36:40.340 --> 00:36:43.790
as like a fun game
and a way to get

00:36:43.790 --> 00:36:47.030
to know each other--
like, a friend of mine

00:36:47.030 --> 00:36:51.440
texted me yesterday
and she said my partner

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:53.930
and I finally did
the 36 questions.

00:36:53.930 --> 00:36:58.910
And they have been together
for 15 years or something.

00:36:58.910 --> 00:37:01.670
And she's like, I learned
new things about him,

00:37:01.670 --> 00:37:03.420
and I was so surprised.

00:37:03.420 --> 00:37:06.470
So I think the value
of it sometimes

00:37:06.470 --> 00:37:10.160
is just you learn things that
you wouldn't necessarily know.

00:37:10.160 --> 00:37:13.430
And it's not like that things
are these necessarily deeply

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:14.480
revealing things.

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:17.210
Sometimes they're just
interesting facts.

00:37:17.210 --> 00:37:20.480
And I think if you position
it that way-- it's not like,

00:37:20.480 --> 00:37:25.340
hey, let's sit down and talk
about our feelings, which

00:37:25.340 --> 00:37:29.780
sometimes Mark and I say to
each other ironically as a way

00:37:29.780 --> 00:37:34.460
to actually talk
about our feelings.

00:37:34.460 --> 00:37:38.170
Because that feels like a
ridiculous thing to say,

00:37:38.170 --> 00:37:39.950
but I think it's
like, oh, hey, look,

00:37:39.950 --> 00:37:42.080
I think this would
be fun, let's try it.

00:37:42.080 --> 00:37:44.857
Because it is fun.

00:37:44.857 --> 00:37:46.190
LOGAN URY: And you can blame us.

00:37:46.190 --> 00:37:48.980
You can be like, I went
to this thing at Google.

00:37:48.980 --> 00:37:51.680
MANDY LEN CATRON: Totally.

00:37:51.680 --> 00:37:53.540
AUDIENCE: You talk about
good relationships,

00:37:53.540 --> 00:37:56.060
great relationships,
complicated relationships.

00:37:56.060 --> 00:38:00.440
And my question is if you
are in a relationship that

00:38:00.440 --> 00:38:04.464
might be complicated and
it might not be great,

00:38:04.464 --> 00:38:06.380
do you think that there
is a chance for people

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:08.780
to fall in love again?

00:38:08.780 --> 00:38:12.702
Or do you think once things
are broken, they're broken?

00:38:12.702 --> 00:38:14.160
MANDY LEN CATRON:
You know, I'm not

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:16.490
very absolute about anything.

00:38:16.490 --> 00:38:19.190
I'm sort of wary of
really fixed rules.

00:38:19.190 --> 00:38:23.480
So I guess I would say of
course there's a chance.

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:30.650
But I do think we tend to create
these patterns of interactions

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:35.880
with other people, and a lot of
research suggests this as well.

00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:39.350
And it's really difficult
to break those patterns,

00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:41.820
but I do think it is
possible to change things.

00:38:41.820 --> 00:38:47.540
This is like another tip related
to your question earlier.

00:38:47.540 --> 00:38:51.680
So John Gottman, famous
relationship psychologist,

00:38:51.680 --> 00:38:56.780
talks about basically having
a relationship bank account,

00:38:56.780 --> 00:38:59.180
and you want to always
keep it in the block.

00:38:59.180 --> 00:39:03.140
And he suggests that you need
like five positive interactions

00:39:03.140 --> 00:39:05.640
for every one
negative interaction,

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:09.560
and he has lots of ways
to and incorporate these

00:39:09.560 --> 00:39:11.090
into a relationship.

00:39:11.090 --> 00:39:17.130
But really, you can practice
positive interactions,

00:39:17.130 --> 00:39:19.670
and you can train yourself
to do more of them.

00:39:19.670 --> 00:39:21.530
And getting that
ratio up I think

00:39:21.530 --> 00:39:24.650
goes a long way towards
relationship satisfaction.

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:28.160
And so it's just little things
like touching your partner

00:39:28.160 --> 00:39:30.830
on the shoulder and being
like, hey, how was your day

00:39:30.830 --> 00:39:32.360
or saying, thank you.

00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:34.160
Thank you goes a long way--

00:39:34.160 --> 00:39:36.770
and just like thanks
for taking out the trash

00:39:36.770 --> 00:39:40.040
or doing the laundry
or whatever--

00:39:40.040 --> 00:39:43.880
just little, small,
positive interactions.

00:39:43.880 --> 00:39:47.992
So I think, yeah,
everything's changeable.

00:39:47.992 --> 00:39:49.700
AUDIENCE: I have two
if that's all right.

00:39:49.700 --> 00:39:50.750
One's just a quick one.

00:39:50.750 --> 00:39:55.056
You mentioned a word, I
think "amato normativity."

00:39:55.056 --> 00:39:56.930
Spellcheck or spelling
on that would be good,

00:39:56.930 --> 00:39:58.220
so I can Google it.

00:39:58.220 --> 00:39:59.420
MANDY LEN CATRON: Yeah.

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:03.410
It's a-m-a-t-o
n-o-r-m-a-t-i-v-i-t-y.

00:40:06.087 --> 00:40:07.670
LOGAN URY: She's an
English professor.

00:40:07.670 --> 00:40:10.310
MANDY LEN CATRON: I always get
nervous spelling things aloud,

00:40:10.310 --> 00:40:12.540
because I'm like, the
stakes are high being

00:40:12.540 --> 00:40:13.880
an English professor.

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:15.250
LOGAN URY: Google has good--

00:40:15.250 --> 00:40:16.000
it would help you.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:17.500
MANDY LEN CATRON:
Amato normativity.

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.486
It's spelled exactly
like it sounds.

00:40:19.486 --> 00:40:21.730
AUDIENCE: Got it.

00:40:21.730 --> 00:40:24.660
That was my guess,
so made me feel good.

00:40:24.660 --> 00:40:28.640
And so the main question is that
there is a concept or this idea

00:40:28.640 --> 00:40:31.910
that everyone is our
mirror, and there's a saying

00:40:31.910 --> 00:40:33.980
that if you can
spot it, you got it.

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:38.510
And relationships fail when
we see in others qualities

00:40:38.510 --> 00:40:42.020
that we dislike about
ourselves, and similarly,

00:40:42.020 --> 00:40:44.390
if you admire someone, it's
because you see something

00:40:44.390 --> 00:40:46.610
in them that you
have yet to own.

00:40:46.610 --> 00:40:50.570
So my question is, is that B.S.?

00:40:50.570 --> 00:40:54.580
Do you ascribe to that, or
what are your thoughts on that?

00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:57.500
It's kind of like a how do you
fall in love with yourself type

00:40:57.500 --> 00:40:58.190
question.

00:40:58.190 --> 00:40:59.870
MANDY LEN CATRON:
That's interesting.

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:03.470
I'm not sure what I think
about that, to be honest.

00:41:03.470 --> 00:41:07.580
I mean, I do think being in a
relationship with someone who

00:41:07.580 --> 00:41:11.630
likes you makes you
like yourself more,

00:41:11.630 --> 00:41:15.560
and I do think liking your
partner goes a long way.

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:17.960
I mean, I don't think we
talk about liking enough.

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:21.290
We talk about loving a lot, but
we don't talk that much about

00:41:21.290 --> 00:41:22.580
liking.

00:41:22.580 --> 00:41:25.490
And there's this thing
that psychologists

00:41:25.490 --> 00:41:28.160
have written about called the
Michelangelo effect, which

00:41:28.160 --> 00:41:31.370
is really if you see
the best in your partner

00:41:31.370 --> 00:41:36.230
that they will aspire to become
the person you see in them.

00:41:36.230 --> 00:41:38.750
And that goes both ways.

00:41:38.750 --> 00:41:43.460
So if your partner
sees the best in you,

00:41:43.460 --> 00:41:46.280
then you will aspire to be
the person that they imagined.

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:50.000
So I suspect that
there's a huge benefit

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.450
in noticing the great
things about your partner

00:41:53.450 --> 00:41:56.990
and paying attention to
them and complimenting them.

00:41:56.990 --> 00:42:03.960
And this is something that I try
to do in my relationship a lot,

00:42:03.960 --> 00:42:06.630
and it's also just nice
to be complimented.

00:42:06.630 --> 00:42:10.650
So I would say be
in a relationship

00:42:10.650 --> 00:42:13.780
with someone who
notices the good in you,

00:42:13.780 --> 00:42:16.794
and notice the good
in other people.

00:42:16.794 --> 00:42:18.710
LOGAN URY: Is that advice,
though, that you've

00:42:18.710 --> 00:42:20.327
given other people,
where you say,

00:42:20.327 --> 00:42:22.910
you have to love yourself before
you can be in a relationship?

00:42:22.910 --> 00:42:24.680
MANDY LEN CATRON: Yeah, I
don't know if that's true.

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:26.780
I kind of feel like
that's crappy advice,

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:30.290
because there are
plenty of people

00:42:30.290 --> 00:42:32.780
who don't love
themselves, who probably

00:42:32.780 --> 00:42:36.886
have a lot of self-loathing
who are in relationships.

00:42:36.886 --> 00:42:38.510
Obviously, it's great
to love yourself,

00:42:38.510 --> 00:42:41.210
but I think it is much
easier to love yourself

00:42:41.210 --> 00:42:44.011
when you're with
someone who likes you.

00:42:44.011 --> 00:42:45.760
And I've been in
relationships with people

00:42:45.760 --> 00:42:49.000
I loved who love me that I'm not
sure we liked each other that

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:50.860
much.

00:42:50.860 --> 00:42:53.170
AUDIENCE: Just to follow up
on your previous answers,

00:42:53.170 --> 00:42:55.750
you said there are a lot of
people who loathe themselves

00:42:55.750 --> 00:42:57.004
who are in relationships.

00:42:57.004 --> 00:42:59.170
Do you think they're in
healthy, good relationships?

00:42:59.170 --> 00:43:01.420
MANDY LEN CATRON: I don't know.

00:43:01.420 --> 00:43:02.097
I don't know.

00:43:02.097 --> 00:43:04.180
I don't know if I'm ready
to answer this question.

00:43:04.180 --> 00:43:05.846
Because I think it's
really interesting,

00:43:05.846 --> 00:43:09.570
but my instinct is that the
answer to this should be no.

00:43:09.570 --> 00:43:11.990
But I don't really
know if that's true.

00:43:11.990 --> 00:43:15.190
So I'd have to do a little
research to figure that out.

00:43:15.190 --> 00:43:18.160
To what extent does
liking yourself

00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:20.650
make you happy in
your own relationship?

00:43:20.650 --> 00:43:25.030
It probably goes fairly far.

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:26.680
I'm sure it makes a difference.

00:43:29.890 --> 00:43:32.170
That's an unsatisfying answer.

00:43:32.170 --> 00:43:33.940
I just want to get it right.

00:43:33.940 --> 00:43:35.245
So I don't know.

00:43:35.245 --> 00:43:36.620
LOGAN URY: Maybe
we'll submit it.

00:43:36.620 --> 00:43:38.869
MANDY LEN CATRON: Yeah,
submit it to my advice column,

00:43:38.869 --> 00:43:41.680
and I'll do some research
and I'll write about this.

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:45.430
Because I would actually
like to know this answer.

00:43:45.430 --> 00:43:47.680
AUDIENCE: If you could have
dinner with anyone, living

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:49.486
or dead, who would it be?

00:43:49.486 --> 00:43:50.860
MANDY LEN CATRON:
You know what's

00:43:50.860 --> 00:43:57.415
so funny is I was looking over
the 36 questions recently,

00:43:57.415 --> 00:43:59.540
and it's been, like, three
years since we did them.

00:43:59.540 --> 00:44:01.930
And I realized, I don't
remember any of my answers

00:44:01.930 --> 00:44:06.200
or Mark's answers,
or I remember a few.

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:08.170
But that one I couldn't
remember the answer,

00:44:08.170 --> 00:44:11.650
so I decided that I needed
to come up with an answer.

00:44:11.650 --> 00:44:13.120
And actually, I
decided it would be

00:44:13.120 --> 00:44:18.220
my dad's mother, my grandmother,
who died when I was 13.

00:44:18.220 --> 00:44:22.420
Because I was able to interview
my mom's mom, my grandmother,

00:44:22.420 --> 00:44:25.170
about her love story for
this book and write about it.

00:44:25.170 --> 00:44:29.080
She has a fantastic love story.

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:30.970
She met my grandfather.

00:44:30.970 --> 00:44:34.240
So they lived in this
tiny, little coal mining

00:44:34.240 --> 00:44:38.900
camp in rural Appalachia, like
in the hollers of Virginia.

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:41.620
And she met my
grandfather when he

00:44:41.620 --> 00:44:43.930
was on leave from World War II.

00:44:43.930 --> 00:44:46.930
And she was 13 and he was 29.

00:44:46.930 --> 00:44:49.640
I know.

00:44:49.640 --> 00:44:52.660
And they spent two weeks
together just chatting,

00:44:52.660 --> 00:44:56.620
and then he went back to
France and fought in Normandy.

00:44:56.620 --> 00:45:00.242
And then he came home and was
like, well, let's get married.

00:45:00.242 --> 00:45:01.450
And that was two years later.

00:45:01.450 --> 00:45:03.970
So she was 15 and he was
31 when they got married,

00:45:03.970 --> 00:45:05.590
and then they had
eight children.

00:45:05.590 --> 00:45:08.270
And he died when I was four,
and she never remarried.

00:45:08.270 --> 00:45:10.780
Anyway, it's such an
interesting story to me,

00:45:10.780 --> 00:45:13.570
and I loved talking
to her about it.

00:45:13.570 --> 00:45:17.890
So I'd love to be able to
interview my other grandmother

00:45:17.890 --> 00:45:20.977
and find out her love story.

00:45:20.977 --> 00:45:22.810
AUDIENCE: Kind of going
back to the question

00:45:22.810 --> 00:45:27.980
about if you don't like yourself
but you're in a relationship--

00:45:27.980 --> 00:45:30.240
I'm more interested
in how would you

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:35.440
go about-- what's your process
for making a study like that?

00:45:35.440 --> 00:45:38.230
Do you just find
couples in relationships

00:45:38.230 --> 00:45:42.370
and ask them, do you hate
yourself but love this--

00:45:42.370 --> 00:45:44.980
I'm curious, actually, how would
you run any of your studies

00:45:44.980 --> 00:45:47.064
that you do for research
and do research for this?

00:45:47.064 --> 00:45:48.854
MANDY LEN CATRON: I
don't do these studies.

00:45:48.854 --> 00:45:51.160
So what I would do is I would
turn to one of my friends

00:45:51.160 --> 00:45:53.980
who's a psychologist
and say, can you

00:45:53.980 --> 00:45:58.520
do this study and
I'll write about it?

00:45:58.520 --> 00:46:05.780
But I think there are ways
for measuring self-esteem,

00:46:05.780 --> 00:46:09.500
and there are ways for measuring
relationship satisfaction.

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:13.460
Psychologists have
created tools for this,

00:46:13.460 --> 00:46:15.830
and I guess you would
just compare those two.

00:46:15.830 --> 00:46:19.190
But I'm not a psychologist,
so I don't know.

00:46:19.190 --> 00:46:21.960
I just read a lot of psychology.

00:46:21.960 --> 00:46:23.960
LOGAN URY: Just to give
you an example if you're

00:46:23.960 --> 00:46:25.584
curious around the
background-- so they

00:46:25.584 --> 00:46:27.500
could likely do a
longitudinal study

00:46:27.500 --> 00:46:31.580
where they could track a
series of people over something

00:46:31.580 --> 00:46:33.350
like four years,
and then they would

00:46:33.350 --> 00:46:35.060
say, how much do
you like yourself

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:36.170
and how happy is
your relationship?

00:46:36.170 --> 00:46:37.753
And they could track
it and they could

00:46:37.753 --> 00:46:40.730
see this person consistently
didn't like themselves

00:46:40.730 --> 00:46:42.650
and they consistently
had these relationships.

00:46:42.650 --> 00:46:44.733
This person, when they
started to like themselves,

00:46:44.733 --> 00:46:45.709
we saw these changes.

00:46:45.709 --> 00:46:47.750
And then if there was a
statistically significant

00:46:47.750 --> 00:46:50.180
difference, they might be
able to say something like,

00:46:50.180 --> 00:46:52.014
when people like
themselves they start to be

00:46:52.014 --> 00:46:53.138
in healthier relationships.

00:46:53.138 --> 00:46:55.260
MANDY LEN CATRON: See, we
have a psych major here.

00:46:55.260 --> 00:46:57.770
She's very handy.

00:46:57.770 --> 00:46:59.750
AUDIENCE: My question
would be, what makes

00:46:59.750 --> 00:47:01.610
a great relationship great?

00:47:01.610 --> 00:47:05.070
And what is the difference
with a good relationship?

00:47:05.070 --> 00:47:07.635
Is it all the
emotional connection?

00:47:07.635 --> 00:47:10.010
MANDY LEN CATRON: What makes
a great relationship great--

00:47:10.010 --> 00:47:12.090
so I've thought
about this a lot,

00:47:12.090 --> 00:47:16.640
and I think the short
answer is kindness.

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:21.050
So much of the psychological
research on romantic love

00:47:21.050 --> 00:47:26.030
can be summarized as
being kind to someone

00:47:26.030 --> 00:47:28.010
and having them be kind to you.

00:47:28.010 --> 00:47:34.900
So I think a good rule for
gauging a relationship is, am I

00:47:34.900 --> 00:47:38.050
able to be kind to my partner?

00:47:38.050 --> 00:47:40.270
And are they kind to me?

00:47:40.270 --> 00:47:42.610
And I think if the answer
to either of those questions

00:47:42.610 --> 00:47:47.380
is no, then you should
really think about why

00:47:47.380 --> 00:47:49.332
you're in that relationship.

00:47:49.332 --> 00:47:51.290
AUDIENCE: After your
talk, I realized we mainly

00:47:51.290 --> 00:47:54.840
discuss about the relationship
between two people,

00:47:54.840 --> 00:47:56.610
but often in the
actual real world

00:47:56.610 --> 00:48:00.060
it's like, I come from my
family and my girlfriend also

00:48:00.060 --> 00:48:01.400
comes from a family.

00:48:01.400 --> 00:48:03.400
And I guess at certain
points, she would ask me,

00:48:03.400 --> 00:48:05.840
hey, maybe it's time
for us to get married.

00:48:05.840 --> 00:48:08.220
Maybe it's not herself,
maybe just some pressure

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:10.430
from her family,
something like that.

00:48:10.430 --> 00:48:12.660
I'm not sure in that
situation how should

00:48:12.660 --> 00:48:14.880
I talk with her
about that point.

00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:18.050
Because I myself, I
feel like maybe we

00:48:18.050 --> 00:48:21.230
should slowly get in that stage
and then maybe get married.

00:48:21.230 --> 00:48:25.190
But what if her family-- hey,
it's time for us to get a baby

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:27.112
or for some biological
reason, maybe you

00:48:27.112 --> 00:48:29.570
should get a baby as soon as
possible, something like that?

00:48:29.570 --> 00:48:31.830
I'm not sure how would
you deal with that case

00:48:31.830 --> 00:48:34.800
if your girlfriend is
coming up with that issue.

00:48:34.800 --> 00:48:38.460
MANDY LEN CATRON: Yeah,
I mean, I don't know.

00:48:38.460 --> 00:48:42.820
But I think what you're asking
a really important question,

00:48:42.820 --> 00:48:44.880
and it's important
to acknowledge what's

00:48:44.880 --> 00:48:46.380
at the heart of
this question, which

00:48:46.380 --> 00:48:53.580
is that love is very much not
just a feeling but a practice.

00:48:53.580 --> 00:48:56.210
And that practice is
very much controlled

00:48:56.210 --> 00:48:59.270
by our social environments.

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:01.970
And that can be everything
from our immediate family

00:49:01.970 --> 00:49:06.020
to a religious belief to
a cultural background,

00:49:06.020 --> 00:49:10.610
and all of these things
indicate how people

00:49:10.610 --> 00:49:12.620
think about romantic love.

00:49:12.620 --> 00:49:17.090
My dad grew up in
the rural South,

00:49:17.090 --> 00:49:24.610
and he has really traditional
ideas about love-- traditional

00:49:24.610 --> 00:49:27.140
as in the past 100
years, I guess,

00:49:27.140 --> 00:49:29.340
how it's been
practiced in America.

00:49:29.340 --> 00:49:35.660
And so he is waiting
for my partner

00:49:35.660 --> 00:49:38.120
to decide that he
wants to marry me,

00:49:38.120 --> 00:49:41.270
and I'm like, that's not
how our relationship works.

00:49:41.270 --> 00:49:45.320
But it's really difficult
to cross that cultural gap.

00:49:45.320 --> 00:49:47.570
AUDIENCE: Actually
what my [INAUDIBLE]..

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:49.820
MANDY LEN CATRON:
Yeah, so I don't

00:49:49.820 --> 00:49:52.610
think I have a good answer
for how to deal with this,

00:49:52.610 --> 00:49:57.980
but my advice would be to seek
out stories and experiences

00:49:57.980 --> 00:50:00.920
from other people who've
been in this situation.

00:50:00.920 --> 00:50:04.070
Because really, if we
think love stories give us

00:50:04.070 --> 00:50:06.590
scripts and scripts tell
us how we can possibly

00:50:06.590 --> 00:50:09.030
behave in a given
number of situations,

00:50:09.030 --> 00:50:12.590
then gathering as many of
those scripts as possible

00:50:12.590 --> 00:50:15.180
will give you more options
for how you might handle it.

00:50:15.180 --> 00:50:16.430
AUDIENCE: So more [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:16.430 --> 00:50:18.710
MANDY LEN CATRON:
Yeah, basically.

00:50:18.710 --> 00:50:21.320
AUDIENCE: So it seems like
in relationships today,

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:24.300
the key metric to
success is longevity,

00:50:24.300 --> 00:50:27.470
and I was wondering if you
subscribe to that metric.

00:50:27.470 --> 00:50:33.790
And also, so you were talking
about marriages today,

00:50:33.790 --> 00:50:35.630
that there's a
modern phenomenon--

00:50:35.630 --> 00:50:37.910
relatively modern
phenomenon-- of marriages

00:50:37.910 --> 00:50:40.310
being very passionate
and romantic.

00:50:40.310 --> 00:50:43.510
And so if longevity
is a good metric,

00:50:43.510 --> 00:50:46.790
do we have to redefine
our idea of what

00:50:46.790 --> 00:50:49.970
marriage should be like?

00:50:49.970 --> 00:50:51.710
MANDY LEN CATRON:
So first I'll say

00:50:51.710 --> 00:50:54.980
I don't know that
longevity is a good metric.

00:50:54.980 --> 00:50:57.680
I don't think of it
as a good metric.

00:50:57.680 --> 00:50:59.480
I guess I feel
complicated about it.

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:03.200
Because like you were saying
this is your anniversary

00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:04.750
and I was like,
congratulations--

00:51:04.750 --> 00:51:06.890
LOGAN URY: Only of having
lunch at Big Table.

00:51:09.105 --> 00:51:10.730
MANDY LEN CATRON:
And so I was thinking

00:51:10.730 --> 00:51:15.170
about I have this impulse
to congratulate people,

00:51:15.170 --> 00:51:18.860
and yet longevity
doesn't really tell you

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:22.196
anything about the quality
of our relationship at all.

00:51:22.196 --> 00:51:23.570
I know people
who've been married

00:51:23.570 --> 00:51:26.060
for a very long time who
don't seem particularly

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:27.290
happy to be together.

00:51:29.940 --> 00:51:31.940
And so I do think
we would benefit

00:51:31.940 --> 00:51:40.310
from coming up with better
metrics, kindness being one.

00:51:40.310 --> 00:51:44.250
And what was the second
part of your question?

00:51:44.250 --> 00:51:47.780
AUDIENCE: Well, based on the
premise of longevity being

00:51:47.780 --> 00:51:50.735
a good metric, do we have to
redefine how we see marriage

00:51:50.735 --> 00:51:52.334
in terms of cash-in?

00:51:52.334 --> 00:51:53.750
MANDY LEN CATRON:
And I will say I

00:51:53.750 --> 00:51:57.290
do think we need to redefine it
regardless, because the fact is

00:51:57.290 --> 00:51:59.520
we live in a culture,
like it or not,

00:51:59.520 --> 00:52:03.110
that values
long-term commitment.

00:52:03.110 --> 00:52:07.490
And really, most people aspire
to long-term commitment,

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:12.300
and I don't think that's
going to change anytime soon.

00:52:12.300 --> 00:52:16.520
So I do think we would
benefit from changing

00:52:16.520 --> 00:52:20.510
our expectations of marriage for
sure or long-term relationships

00:52:20.510 --> 00:52:21.910
in general.

00:52:21.910 --> 00:52:23.590
There is this
research that shows--

00:52:23.590 --> 00:52:26.330
it's by this psychologist
named Eli Finkel,

00:52:26.330 --> 00:52:29.510
and he's found that,
essentially, marriage

00:52:29.510 --> 00:52:32.120
has climbed over
the past, I don't

00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:33.770
know, 60, 70 years--
or maybe even

00:52:33.770 --> 00:52:37.404
longer than that-- climbed
Maslow's hierarchy of needs.

00:52:37.404 --> 00:52:39.320
I don't know if you guys
are familiar with us,

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:42.480
but it's basic needs
like food, shelter.

00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:44.600
And then it's like
belonging and love,

00:52:44.600 --> 00:52:48.110
and then it's self-actualization
up at the top.

00:52:48.110 --> 00:52:51.980
And what we increasingly want
and expect from our marriages

00:52:51.980 --> 00:52:53.660
is self-actualization.

00:52:53.660 --> 00:52:56.120
So we're looking
to this one person

00:52:56.120 --> 00:52:59.660
to give us the best
sex we've ever had

00:52:59.660 --> 00:53:03.500
and be like a perfect
parent and to have

00:53:03.500 --> 00:53:09.350
stimulating conversations about
the latest Malcolm Gladwell

00:53:09.350 --> 00:53:10.040
book.

00:53:10.040 --> 00:53:13.730
And so it's like we want all
these things from this one

00:53:13.730 --> 00:53:16.250
person, and essentially,
what he suggests

00:53:16.250 --> 00:53:18.110
is that's really unrealistic.

00:53:18.110 --> 00:53:21.650
And we would benefit
from diversifying

00:53:21.650 --> 00:53:23.420
the ways in which
we meet those needs

00:53:23.420 --> 00:53:26.660
for self-actualization so we're
getting them from other people.

00:53:26.660 --> 00:53:31.310
The other really interesting and
not so good side effect of that

00:53:31.310 --> 00:53:34.070
is that the best
marriages are probably

00:53:34.070 --> 00:53:38.000
more happy and satisfied
than ever before,

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.790
but fewer and fewer
people are achieving

00:53:40.790 --> 00:53:42.770
that sort of pinnacle
of self-actualization

00:53:42.770 --> 00:53:43.979
within a marriage.

00:53:43.979 --> 00:53:45.770
And one of the things
that he's pointed out

00:53:45.770 --> 00:53:48.860
is that increasingly
satisfaction in marriage

00:53:48.860 --> 00:53:52.850
is only accessible to
people of upper-middle class

00:53:52.850 --> 00:53:57.027
and upper class, because it
requires-- like this date

00:53:57.027 --> 00:53:58.610
night, which I was
saying is so great,

00:53:58.610 --> 00:54:00.860
but it requires
financial flexibility

00:54:00.860 --> 00:54:03.000
to be able to do
something like that.

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.839
Especially if you
have children, you

00:54:05.839 --> 00:54:07.380
need to be able to
hire a babysitter,

00:54:07.380 --> 00:54:11.540
or you need to not be working
65 hours a week or whatever.

00:54:11.540 --> 00:54:14.300
So having the time to invest--

00:54:14.300 --> 00:54:16.290
like the more you invest
in your relationship,

00:54:16.290 --> 00:54:17.960
the more you get out of it--

00:54:17.960 --> 00:54:21.110
but having the time and
resources to do that,

00:54:21.110 --> 00:54:22.830
not that many people have that.

00:54:22.830 --> 00:54:26.930
So on the whole, I think we
need to really rethink marriage,

00:54:26.930 --> 00:54:28.724
but that'll be another book.

00:54:28.724 --> 00:54:29.390
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:32.510
My name is Ricardo, and I
believe you mentioned earlier

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:35.454
that you've seen
relationships where

00:54:35.454 --> 00:54:36.870
you're in love
with another person

00:54:36.870 --> 00:54:38.494
but maybe you don't
like them right now

00:54:38.494 --> 00:54:39.855
or every or something.

00:54:39.855 --> 00:54:42.320
And I was wondering,
what do you think

00:54:42.320 --> 00:54:45.530
keeps the love alive in
such kinds of relationships

00:54:45.530 --> 00:54:48.080
when you just don't
like your partner?

00:54:48.080 --> 00:54:50.300
MANDY LEN CATRON: I don't know.

00:54:50.300 --> 00:54:51.680
That's a great question.

00:54:51.680 --> 00:54:54.180
Why do we stay in
relationships with people

00:54:54.180 --> 00:54:55.205
we don't like that much?

00:54:58.000 --> 00:54:58.710
I don't know.

00:54:58.710 --> 00:55:02.010
I mean, I think maybe I
can only speak for myself

00:55:02.010 --> 00:55:03.750
on this particular point.

00:55:03.750 --> 00:55:08.850
And I definitely stayed in
a relationship with somebody

00:55:08.850 --> 00:55:10.290
who I really, deeply loved.

00:55:10.290 --> 00:55:13.690
Like, I felt this strong
sense of intimacy,

00:55:13.690 --> 00:55:17.730
and there was a lot
of physical attraction

00:55:17.730 --> 00:55:20.880
and there was a lot
of shared history.

00:55:20.880 --> 00:55:24.060
And the problems is we were
really critical of each other

00:55:24.060 --> 00:55:27.720
all the time, and
criticism has been shown

00:55:27.720 --> 00:55:30.370
to really erode relationships.

00:55:30.370 --> 00:55:34.560
So I think it was
really a matter of time,

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:38.210
but I think part of what kept me
in that relationship, or maybe

00:55:38.210 --> 00:55:40.680
even both of us, was the
sense that we had already

00:55:40.680 --> 00:55:42.350
invested a lot.

00:55:42.350 --> 00:55:45.060
I don't know if you're familiar
with the economic theory

00:55:45.060 --> 00:55:46.840
of sunk costs.

00:55:46.840 --> 00:55:49.500
It's like you've already
paid for these tickets

00:55:49.500 --> 00:55:51.810
to the baseball game, and
even though you have a cold,

00:55:51.810 --> 00:55:54.300
you're like, I'm going to go
to this baseball game anyway,

00:55:54.300 --> 00:55:58.230
even though I'd rather stay
home and watch a movie.

00:55:58.230 --> 00:56:01.680
So I think it's like I'm going
to stick out this relationship

00:56:01.680 --> 00:56:03.730
because I've been
in it for so long,

00:56:03.730 --> 00:56:06.810
and the work of finding a new
partner is really intimidating

00:56:06.810 --> 00:56:10.020
and the other side
feels like very unknown.

00:56:10.020 --> 00:56:14.460
And if not perfect,
it's like it's familiar.

00:56:14.460 --> 00:56:20.600
And I think that that sort
of inertia is powerful.

00:56:20.600 --> 00:56:22.886
It's scary to end
a relationship.

00:56:22.886 --> 00:56:24.260
LOGAN URY: Well,
Mandy, thank you

00:56:24.260 --> 00:56:26.390
so much for being vulnerable
with us and coming.

00:56:26.390 --> 00:56:27.530
It was really great
to talk to you.

00:56:27.530 --> 00:56:27.720
MANDY LEN CATRON:
Thanks for having me.

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:28.550
This was so much fun.

00:56:28.550 --> 00:56:29.216
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:56:29.216 --> 00:56:30.080
Thank you.

